article.description: Janell Burse and Katie Smith both scored 16 points to earn the franchise's first playoff berth in its five-year history.
article.headline: Burse, Smith have 16 points each
article.linkText: Lynx clinch first playoff berth in team history
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The key word for the Minnesota Lynx now is
"noise."

As in, what the team hopes to make in the postseason.

"We're excited about being there - but not just about being
there. We want to make some noise in the playoffs," said Lynx
coach Suzie McConnell Serio after Minnesota's 69-66 win Wednesday
night over the Phoenix Mercury.

With Janell Burse's block of a last-second 3-point attempt, the
Lynx (18-14) reached the postseason for the first time in its
five-year history.

"It feels good and I'm the one who has been here the longest,"
said Smith, who has spent her entire WNBA career with Minnesota.
"But it was almost expected in a way because of the talent we have
and the way we work."

Burse and Katie Smith scored 16 points.

Although the Lynx (18-14) have two games to play, the team can
finish no worse than fourth following Seattle's loss to San Antonio
on Wednesday night.

Seattle (16-16) and Sacramento (17-14) are fighting for the last
playoff spot from the Western Conference.

However, the Lynx weren't told about the Seattle loss until
after the game.

Smith said that didn't matter. They wanted to earn the berth
themselves.

"It is amazing but it does feel good to have a chance and go in
there and make some noise in a whole new season," added Smith, the
fourth-leading scorer in the league. She was held to two points in
the first half.

Minnesota faces first-place Los Angeles on Thursday on the road
and finishes the regular season at home on Saturday against Eastern
Conference champ Detroit.

"We let them jump on us early and they really hurt us on the
offensive glass," said Mercury coach John Shumate.

"We dug a hole for ourselves. We made a good run but just wound
up fouling the wrong the person."

Minnesota outrebounded Phoenix 35-24 and made six straight free
throws in the final 22.8 seconds.

The Lynx, who have won three of their last four, led by as much
as 12 in the second half.

But Phoenix (7-25) went on a 14-2 run and tied it at 61 after
Anna DeForge made a layup with 1:20 left.

"Both teams made big shots when needed and put the pressure on
defensively," said DeForge. "We just allowed them to get too many
offensive boards."

Burse hit a layup with 52 seconds left and Smith made two free
throws with 22 seconds remaining.

Slobodanka Tuvic followed her miss with 16 seconds left but
Tamika Williams hit two free throws with 15 seconds remaining to
put Minnesota up 67-63.

DeForge, who led Phoenix with 18 points, hit a 3-pointer with 12
seconds left. Smith made two more free throws with 7 seconds left
and Burse blocked a last-second 3-point attempt by Tuvic.

Tuvic and Adrian Williams added 14 points for Phoenix, which has
the worst record in the WNBA.

The Mercury had beaten Minnesota 56-49 in their last meeting
Aug. 6 in Phoenix.

Burse scored 12 of the Lynx' first 14 points as Minnesota took a
35-27 lead at halftime.
